[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][mmlu] sample 37/100 path 1/3 answer="To find \\(a^3 + b^3 + c^3\\), we can utilize the identity:\n\n\\[a^3 + b^3 + c^3 - 3abc = (a + b + c)(a^2 + b^2 + c^2 - ab - ac - bc)\\]\n\nGiven that \\(a + b + c = 6\\) and \\(abc = -12\\), let's first calculate \\(a^2 + b^2 + c^2\\). Using the square of sum formula:\n\n\\[a^2 + b^2 + c^2 = (a + b + c)^2 - 2(ab + ac + bc)\\]\n\\[= 6^2 - 2 \\cdot 5\\]\n\\[= 36 - 10\\]\n\\[= 26\\]\n\nNow, substituting these values into our identity:\n\n\\[a^3 + b^3 + c^3 - 3(-12) = 6(26 - (-12))\\]\n\\[= 6(26 + 12)\\]\n\\[= 6 \\cdot 38\\]\n\\[= 228\\]\n\nFinally, subtract 3 times abc from this result to get \\(a^3 + b^3 + c^3\\):\n\n\\[a^3 + b^3 + c^3 = 228 - 3(-12)\\]\n\\[= 228 + 36\\]\n\\[= 264\\]\n\nHowever, none of the given options match this result. It seems there might be an error in the provided choices or the calculation. Let me review the calculations again carefully to ensure accuracy.\n\nRechecking:\n\\[a^2 + b^2 + c^2 = 36 + 36 = 72"
