[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][mmlu] sample 58/100 path 3/3 answer='To solve this problem, I will go through each statement one by one to determine which one is incorrect and explain my reasoning:\n\n1. **Statement A**: "It shows an association with Down syndrome."\n   - This statement is correct because Hirschsprung disease is known to have a higher prevalence among individuals who carry the BRCA1 or BRCA2 gene mutations, particularly those affected by Lynch syndrome (a variant of BRCA1/BRCA2). While it might not always show association with Down syndrome alone, it does raise concerns about genetic predisposition to certain diseases.\n\n2. **Statement B**: "It is more common in girls than in boys."\n   - This statement is also correct. Studies indicate that Hirschsprung disease is predominantly found in females compared to males. However, it\'s important to note that the exact numbers can vary depending on specific population studies, so this generalization may not hold true for all cases.\n\n3. **Statement C**: "RET is a major susceptibility gene."\n   - This statement is incorrect. Hirschsprung disease is not primarily caused by a single gene mutation but rather by defects in the nervous system of the infant. Mutations in genes like RET do play a role, but they are not considered the primary cause. Instead, they contribute to the overall defect observed in the digestive tract.\n\n4. **Statement D**: "Recurrence risks are greater for long segment disease than for short segment disease."\n   - This statement is accurate. Research indicates that Hirschsprung disease tends to resolve over time when the underlying defect is corrected. Short segments often resolve quickly due to their simpler nature. On the other hand, long segments can persist longer, potentially leading to complications such as bowel obstruction or malabsorption issues if left untreated.\n\nTherefore, the incorrect statement is C, "RET is a major susceptibility gene."'
