[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][mmlu] sample 83/100 path 2/3 answer="Step-by-step reasoning:\n\n1. **Understanding the Evidence**:\n   - The deposition of the witness, taken at the time of the accident, is relevant and provides firsthand information about the circumstances leading up to the incident.\n   \n2. **Admissibility Criteria**:\n   - According to the standard rules of legal proceedings, the deposition is considered admissible if it has been taken under oath.\n   - It should be deemed more probative than any other evidence presented at trial and that the skier has obtained sufficient opportunity to cross-examine the witness.\n   \n3. **Analysis of Options**:\n   - Option A (admissible as former testimony) is correct because the deposition is from before the event and thus can be considered a testimonial record.\n   - Option B (admissible, provided the deposition is more probative than any other evidence) is incorrect because the deposition is not more probative; it is already sufficiently evidentiary.\n   - Option C (inadmissible, because it violates the ski resort's right to confront witnesses against itself) is incorrect because the ski resort does not have the right to confront the witness directly during the course of the trial.\n   - Option D (inadmissible, because it is hearsay not within any recognized exception) is incorrect because the deposition is clearly classified as evidence under standard legal principles.\n\nFinal Answer: The deposition is inadmissible, because it violates the ski resort's right to confront witnesses against itself."
