[self_consistency][qwen2_5_0_5b_instruct][mmlu] sample 86/100 path 2/3 answer="1. According to Shelley's Case, if a conveyance involves a fee simple absolute and it is impossible to convey that fee simple, then the entire remainder of the gift becomes subject to conveyance.\n2. In this case, the property was conveyed with a fee simple absolute, meaning the son has a fee simple right to convey the entire property as described in the grantor's conveyance.\n3. Because the son cannot convey the fee simple, the entire remainder of the gift automatically transfers to his heirs under the terms of the grantor's conveyance.\n4. Since the remainder includes the contingent fee simple of the son, the son will lose both his own fee simple and the remainder of the inheritance upon his failure to fulfill his duty.\n5. Therefore, the son's conveying of the premises to his friend would result in his losing all but the fee simple portion of the remainder.\n6. This means he loses both the fee simple and the remainder of his heirs' interest.\n7. The correct option reflecting these points is D: the son’s succeeding, because the son's conveyance of his life estate to the friend divested the contingent remainder of his heirs."
